Part I - Prosper Loan Data Analysis¶

byMenzi Khumalo¶

Introduction¶

The dataset to be investigated consist of borrower APRs and attributes of 113,937 loans. The attributes included original loan amount, borrower's Prosper rating, loan term, borrower's stated monthly income, as well as many other features such as borrower's employment status, debt to income ratio, current loan status etc. In this analysis I will look at the effects of loan properties on the Borrower APR.

# Create a category of income
income_cat = {'ProsperRating (Alpha)': ['N/A','HR','E','D','C', 'B', 'A', 'AA'],
                    'IncomeRange':['$0','$1-24,999','$25,000-49,999','$50,000-74,999','$75,000-99,999','$100,000+']}
for var in income_cat:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = income_cat[var])
    df_loans[var] = df_loans[var].astype(ordered_var)

Univariate Exploration¶

I will start with the most important features: Borrower APR , Prosper Score, employment and income range which will help me build an intuition of how the numeric values are distributed in the dataset.

Question: How are Borrower APR values distributed in the dataset?

In [7]:
binsize = 2
APR_percentage = df_loans['BorrowerAPR']*100
bins = np.arange(df_loans['BorrowerAPR'].min()*100, df_loans['BorrowerAPR'].max()*100+binsize, binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[10, 5])
plt.hist(x = APR_percentage, bins = bins)
plt.title('Borrower APR Distribution (%)')
plt.xlabel('Borrower Annual Percentage Rate (%)')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.xticks([5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35, 40], ['5','10', '15', '20', '25', '30', '35', '40'])
plt.show()
Observation¶

We see that the Borrower APR is normally distrubuted with the peak between 15 and 20 percent in addition we have some increase in the 35 percent

Conclusions¶

This exploration of Prosper loan data was aimed at identifying what affects Borrower APR: The results show that

  • The high income earners enjoy larger loans at lower APRs than the low income earners.
  • Borrowers with low prosper ratings take smaller loans at higher APRs.
  • Borrower APR and Lender yield are directly positively correlated as when the interest borrowers pays more.
  • Higher loan amounts are more likely to come with lower APRs when compared to small loan amounts.
